    <text id="R127456963T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Union director of military railroads Herman Haupt writes from Chambersburg to
                    Army of the Potomac Quartermaster Rufus Ingalls. Haupt reports that he is moving
                    his repair crews from the Chambersburg area to Alexandria, and comments on
                    Robert E. Lee's withdrawal into Virginia following the Gettysburg campaign of
                    July, 1863.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Received 10 p. m.<lb/> Gen. R. Ingalls, Army of the
                        Potomac:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1863-07-14">July 14, 1863.</date>
                        <name type="place">Chambersburg, Pa.,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>The Winchester road cannot be relied upon for any transportation whatever. The
                    rail is strap iron, the supports rotten, and the lightest engines run off the
                    track continually. I am moving my whole force to Alexandria. You cannot catch
                    Lee by following in his rear. The bridges on the Orange and Alexandria Railroad
                    which are not yet burned should be saved, if possible; also on the Manassas Gap
                    Railroad.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>H. HAUPT,<lb/> Brig.-Gen.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
